===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|emeraude}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|esmeraude}}, from {{etyl|VL.|en}} {{m|la|*esmaralda}}, {{m|la|*esmaraldus}}, variant of {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|smaragdus}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|σμάραγδος}}, {{m|grc|μάραγδος}}, from a {{etyl|sem|en}} language. Compare {{cog|he|בָּרֶקֶת|tr=bareket}} “emerald, flashing gem”, Akkadian {{cog|akk|𒁀𒊏𒄣|tr=baraqu|lit=scintillation}}, {{cog|ar|بَرْق|tr=barq|lit=flashing}}, {{cog|egy|bwyrqꜣ|lit=to sprarkle}}:<hiero>D58-Z7-Z4:D21-N29-Z1-G1-D6</hiero> and loanwords with Semitic etymon such as {{cog|sa|मरकत}} and Persian {{m|fa|زمرد|tr=zomorrod}} (whence Turkish {{m|tr|zümrüt}} and Russian {{m|ru|изумру́д}}).

